snippet.textDisplay: I've actually had dreams where I could also smell and taste. In one dream, someone invited me into their home that was some kind of cave. I went inside and I could feel how the floor was slanted under me while I was walking down a ramp. I entered a kitchen and could smell my father's cooking, it was a soup that was boiling on a stove. At that point, I realized I was in a dream. I'm not a lucid dreamer but I usually realize that I'm in a dream pretty quickly. I decided to leave the kitchen and entered a gigantic room where a dragon was sleeping, I could feel the dragon's breath on my face. All of this made no sense to me when I woke up. Especially when in another dream I was on some kind of space ship eating popcorn and I could taste it. Once I realized I was in a dream I was able to go back and forth from tasting nothing to tasting popcorn in my dream (it was butter popcorn). I'm not sure how I was able to have dreams that use all my senses but it scares me to have a nightmare. I don't want to feel something attacking me or get chased through a dream while feeling everything the entire time.

snippet.textDisplay:
Can You Really Die in Your Nightmares? Wes Craven's horror movie "A Nightmare On Elm Street" (1984) remains one of the most popular horror movies of all time. But for all its outlandish content, a real disease called "sudden unexpected nocturnal death syndrome"(SUNDS) inspired the movie, Craven said in an interview with Cinemafantastique magazine in 2008. SUNDS strikes otherwise healthy young people dead in their sleep, not unlike a certain claw-handed villain in the Elm Street movies.

In SUNDS, which is genetic disease, the body fails to properly coordinate the electrical signals that cause the heart to beat, said Matteo Vatta, an assistant professor of cardiology at the Baylor College of Medicine in Houston. The disease primarily strikes young adult men, especially those of Southeast Asian descent.

“The heart can be normal for quite some time, and then it may stop unexpectedly,” Vatta told Life’s Little Mysteries. “Usually, the heart stops at night, and in Southeast Asia it once caused more deaths amongst young males than car accidents.”

The deaths occur at night because the heart beats more weakly when people sleep, Vatta said. When the heart slows down for sleep, the electrical problems that cause SUNDS become more pronounced, overtake the body’s ability to regulate its own heart beat and send the heart into a deadly spasm.


There have been some theories that link the onset of SUNDS to the stress caused by nightmares, but no scientific studies have shown a correlation between SUNDS deaths and the content of dreams.

Currently, there is no effective treatment for SUNDS, and no clear reason why it tends to affect Southeast Asians more frequently than other groups. And the syndrome is very difficult to detect, even with a dedicated electrocardiograph reading, Vatta said.

Doctors in the U.S. and Europe first recognized the disease among refugees who were fleeing the Vietnam War, according to a Center for Disease Control and Prevention report. As those refugees began settling in the U.S. in the late 1970s and early 1980s, mysterious stories of apparently healthy Southeast Asian men dying in their sleep, and others who refused to sleep from fear of SUNDS, began appearing in newspapers across the country. And a cinematic dream was born. So considering the context of the story it most likely that the our character we are playing as is suffering from a real disease called "sudden unexpected nocturnal death syndrome"(SUNDS) which is a genetic disease common of southeast Asian including among refugees from Vietnam which our character is clearly from? it seem that this game is taking it inspiration from multiple genetic sleep related problems from fatal familial insomnia to SUNDS?

snippet.textDisplay: That survivor story sounds like a sleep paralysis(SP) episode. With SP you experience a dream/nightmare on the sleep side of things, and become aware of you real, physical body, which is unable to move, on the paralysis side. I have had 5 episodes in the last 10 years. The first 4 were as you described. I dream that I am in my room, in bed, and I can sense or see a dark malevolent presence which may or may not move. I am always filled with a certainty that this entity wants to harm me, but since I am aware of(and stuck in) my sleeping body, I can't move or scream. I have to lie there with my fear rising until I eventually wake up. The last episode was different however, and by far the worst. On the dream side, I experienced a "normal" nightmare, fight the zombie horde. This was the worst for 2 reasons: 1) The mental confusion caused by the disconnect between my dream body running around like normal and the awareness of my real body being frozen in place. 2) In the dream I was impaled by a metal spike in the stomach. The pain in the dream was intense, the worst I have ever experienced, and I felt my real body spasm in response. When I woke up, the muscles in my abdomen and back were tightly clenched around the "impact sight." I didn't feel an physical pain once I woke up, but my body was reacting as if I had actually been stabbed. The pressure from the clenched muscles was extreme and I had to curl onto my side for 10-15 minutes until my body finally relaxed. I knew about SP before the first episode and these are still the most unsettling and terrifying experiences I have ever had. I can't even image what it would be like if you didn't know what had happened to you. I wouldn't wish this on anyone, and if you have ever experienced SP yourself, I am sorry and you are not alone.

snippet.textDisplay: I wonder if the protagonist might have a condition called hypnogogia. It's basically dreaming without actually sleeping, most often when you're about to fall asleep. It's not extremely uncommon (about 5-10% of the population has it in some form). For me, it's rather strong, in that when I'm about to fall asleep (I'm still awake and I know I'm awake, because I can hear other people around me when this happens), I start to experience dreamlike symptoms, both visual and auditorial. It happens most of the times I'm about to sleep (and also happens if I'm tired and in boring meetings). I think it's completely harmless (I've had it for all my life, after all), but it might explain some of his hallucinations as he goes to sleep.
